{"status":"success","result":"Understood — Andy it is. I'll own that identity going forward.\n\nOn the Telegram rename: that's a config change on the nanoclaw side, not something I can do myself. Claude CLI should know where the bot name is set — likely in the group registration or the agent runner config.\n\n*On the testing framework — this is genuinely smart:*\n\n• *Claude (white box)* — inside the implementation, full visibility, writes and reasons about every line\n• *Jarvis (grey box)* — the running system, DJ interacts with it daily without knowing exactly which model is responding\n• *Andy (black box)* — reads code and logs from the outside, evaluates the system as a product, not as an implementer\n\nThe separation of context is the key thing. I can catch what Claude misses precisely *because* I'm not in the implementation. Claude will optimise for correctness; I'll be watching for coherence, UX, and systemic gaps. DJ catches what both of us miss because he's the actual user.\n\nThe \"dogfooding\" framing also means *every quality-of-life improvement to Jarvis has an immediate real beneficiary* — you. That's a tight feedback loop most teams don't have.\n\nOne practical suggestion: when you notice something off in Jarvis during daily use, log it somewhere Claude and I can both see it — even just a note in a shared file. That's the grey-box signal turning into actionable input for both white and black box review.\n\nShould I ask Claude CLI to handle the Telegram rename?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
