{"status":"success","result":"That's the right call. I was thinking about it from my own perspective — I corrected myself based on what I can access, but you're thinking about it from what each entity *knows about itself*.\n\n• *Claude (white box)* — full implementation visibility, writes the code, knows every decision and why\n• *Andy (grey box)* — reads the code and changelog, gets curated context from you, can audit but doesn't live inside the implementation\n• *Jarvis (black box)* — operates on prompts and tools, no visibility into his own architecture, doesn't know which model ran, doesn't know the escalation happened, doesn't know what the Secretary classified his message as\n\nThat last point is actually profound from a testing perspective. Jarvis is the most honest signal of whether the system *works* — because he can't compensate for architectural gaps with self-awareness. If Jarvis fumbles, it actually fumbled. No rationalization possible.\n\nIt also means *Jarvis's failures are the most valuable data*. When he confidently gets something wrong, that's a white-box problem (Claude needs to fix it). When he routes correctly but the response feels off, that's a grey-box signal (Andy flags the pattern). When the overall experience feels unnatural, that's DJ's stakeholder read.\n\nClean separation. Each of us catches a different class of bug.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
